CHAPTER I: REUNION\par
\par
It was an undeniably morose scene. Outside of a leather bar in Grand Koopa City, Nameless to walk-ins as the neon sign had long been burnt out and neglected. A tall-lean silhouette was visible against the dim interior lights of the near-empty dive, his hair extending his height by no less than a head. As a lone Koopa sauntered by, he took no notice of the silhouete pulling a Zippo out of its pocket and leaning down to light a Newport. The figure silently enjoyed a few drags, blowing the smoke high up in the air, as if proud of it. Several more people passed, and some were lucky enough to catch a glimpse of the figure's face as their moving synchronized with the headlights of passing cars. All who saw its dour, self-satisfied gaze recognized it immediately, but none stopped to converse. They knew very well that he was above them, both socially and in wealth. The only passerby that dared to confront him was a small boy, still young enough to be ignorant of the unwritten laws of classism.\par
"Oh, gee, it's Larry Koopa! Mr. Larry, I'm your biggest fan! My daddy told me about when you fought Mario himself!"\par
The boy was not mistaken. Leaning against the bar's window frame was none other than the youngest of the Koopa kids, his tight wife-beater nearly concealed behind a black leather jacket. As he shifted his weight onto his feet, the chain that ran from his wallet to a belt loop on his black faded denim jeans jingled with the motion.\par
The boy didn't seem put off by Larry's tough appearance, as so many others around them seemed to. Larry, who had been looking down at his cigarette the entire time, only now glanced up, just long enough to utter an emotionless phrase.\par
"If your Daddy had any kind of fuckin' memory, he'd have also told you I lost."\par
The youngster was stunned at his idol's cursing. Still, he recovered and continued.\par
"Everybody loses a battle now and then. You're still the greatest to me-"\par
The boy barely got the last word out when he saw something fall out of Larry's jeans pocket onto the sidewalk.\par
"God damnit", Larry muttered, the lit cigarette in his mouth garbling his words. "Now the whole pack's gonna be fuckin' dirty."\par
He stooped down to pick it up, and the little boy backed up. Had Larry cared, he would have noticed the youngster was beginning to feel uncomfortable.\par
"What the hell are you doin' on this side of town, anyway?", Larry continued as he brushed off the cigarette pack and stuck it back in his pocket. "Bad shit goes down around here."\par
The boy didn't answer right away. "Then... Why are you here, Mr. Larry?"\par
Larry glared down at the boy, finally taking the smoke out of his mouth. "Because I'm here to do just that... Bad things. Not that it's any of your god damn business, but do you see this bar behind me?"\par
The boy meekly nodded, obviously frightened by Larry's heightened voice and apparent irritation.\par
"There's an empty bottle of Everclear behind the counter in there, and a slutty bitch lying on her stomach in the back tied and gagged with her pussy full of my little white legion and fifty of my hard-earned dollars. Now unless you want me to pound your teeny-tiny face into the pavement, I suggest you scoot your ass back home. Because if you don't, you're going to have to beat me there, because right about now I'm starting to feel like finding your Daddy and punching his fucking lights out. Am I clear?"\par
The boy was starting to back up slowly as sweat trickled off of his brow. Larry only smiled as he watched the youngster turn and high-tail it in the direction that he first came from.\par
After he was gone, Larry stuck the cigarette back in his mouth and took two humongous puffs from it. Had he any decency left, he would've felt guilty for scaring an innocent boy like that, especially one that had obviously looked up to him, at least when he had started talking. As he finished the cigarette and thoughtlessly discarded it on the sidewalk, he heard a faint yell coming from inside the bar. He casually swung his head back to look in, and found the plump, haggard bartender waving him in. He once again slowly leaned back up onto his feet and sauntered in like he owned the place. He knew that, considering his being royalty in this city, he pretty much did. But though the bartender was as aware of his status as he was, he didn't hide the frustration on his face. He spoke sternly to Larry as he wiped down the counter.\par
"I saw all of that out there. You know, you really didn't have to do that."\par
Larry chuckled lazily. "I know. That's why I did it, genius."\par
"If I were you, I would change my choice of words."\par
Larry evoked an insincere smile. "You're right, I'm sorry. That's why I did it, \b asswipe\b0 ."\par
The bartender's face turned red with anger, but he held his tongue. He knew better than to disrespect one of Bowser's children. "I... Called you in about something else."\par
Larry nodded as he pulled the pack of Newports out of his pocket once again. The bartender initially took no notice and continued.\par
"I've been getting alot of complaints about the way to talk to the other patrons, and especially the waitresses. They've accused you of mouthing off to them even worse than you did that boy out there, and if you don't stop, I'll have to do something about it."\par
"Tch. Yeah, right.", Larry jeered as he produced the lighter from another pocket. "You ain't gonna do shit, and you know it."\par
The bartender was becoming more and more furious with each passing moment. He had to struggle to keep his composure.\par
"You... Can't smoke in here. You know that. If you light that, you'll have to put it out."\par
Larry stared at him vacantly as he put the flame to the tip and his mouth to the filter. He said nothing as he took a long, deep drag, and blew it out straight into the bartender's face, sending him into a coughing fit. Larry waited until the man regained his breath to reply.\par
"Make me, big shot."\par
The bartender's countenance was beet-red. As his hands trembled with fury, Larry laughed deeply. "Go ahead, I'm waiting. Make me." He opened his jacket. "I'll even let you take the first shot."\par
The bartender, of course, did nothing, but only marched into the back biting his lip. Larry shot him the middle finger after he was no longer in sight, and headed back out the door. He didn't care if the bartender had anything else to say to him; he had nothing to say back.\par
As he stepped back out of the threshold, he saw something that made him freeze in his tracks.\par
There, parked on the curb with the engine still running and loud but unplaceable bass booming seemingly out of the entire car, was a cherry-red Viper, the deep crimson colour stained purple at the bottom by the meeting of its colour with the light from blue ground-effects. For a moment, he just stood there staring at it, until the engine cut off, the bass subsided and the driver's side scissor-door flung open.\par
He saw smoke before the driver's head even came into view. Once he stepped out of the ride, Larry immediately recognized the bald head and member's only jacket above dark camos, similar to his but bigger and heavier, more suited to the driver's taller, thicker frame.\par
Against the streetlights, the driver was next to invisible as he made his way around the car, his heavy boots crunching the leaf litter that surrounded the gutters. Larry smiled as soon as he had placed him, and it only grew wider as the man approached, stopped inches from his face, and exhaled the entire contents of his lungs through his wide nostrils. Though most of it dissipated before it reached Larry's face, the smell was unmistakeable.\par
"Red hair?", Larry asked, showing more emotion than either the boy or the bartender had seen from him.\par
The dark figure smiled. "You know it. I got a pound of high-grade and a quarter bag of kind bud from D.P. And he threw in a joint of Maui Wowie, just to show his respect."\par
Larry laughed genuinely. "I love that mother fucker. How \b is\b0  Dirty Pete, anyway?"\par
The figure nodded slightly as he spoke. "Good, good, he's been clean ever since the cops busted Ol' Rusty for that storehouse of dime rocks he kept in that old shed next to his place off of Bluevine. I guess seein' your best friend put away for twenty is enough to make anybody give up runnin' a lab."\par
Larry chuckled. "It's sad, Roy. Ol' Rusty was an awesome sonuvabitch. Do you know how many acid trips I used to take with that mother fucker?"\par
Roy nodded. "I know, man, I'll miss him too. I remember when I used to walk in the front door at ten in the morning and you were laid out in the floor with no less than three hookers and five empty tabs lying on the coffee table. I'm surprised the fuzz didn't pick you up when they busted him, knowin' how much you hung around there."\par
"No shit. Lucky I was at home when they did that sting and nabbed him. I still remember the phone ringing when I was kicking Morton's ass at Tekken, pickin' it up and hearing Rusty's voice on the other end tellin' me that he wouldn't see me for a looooong time."\par
"Yeah, I guess it's a good thing he didn't rat you out. He had both the means and a good reason to."\par
"If he had, I would've found a way to light his ass up from outside of those four walls, and he knows that. Besides, he and I go way back. After he told me how long he was gonna be in for, I went straight to the fridge and poured out a whole pint of Bacardi for his old ass. And you know how I love that shit."\par
"Love it?", Roy laughed. "You could fuckin' live on it if you wanted to."\par
"I did, for about a week. Remember?"\par
Roy nodded. "Yeah, but that shit had to stop after the seventh day. You were so fucking wasted that you started comin' onto Wendy's best friend, and I knew she wasn't gonna be havin' that."\par
"Shit, no. I'm glad you stepped in when you did."\par
"That's what brothers are for, isn't it?"\par
"True, true. D'you gotta watch on you?"\par
"Nah, but when I got out of the car, the dash clock said about two, two-thirty. Dad's probably sittin' up at home worrying about us."\par
"Yeah, I know. Are you headin' back?"\par
"Yeah. Want me to give you a ride?"\par
"Hell yeah. I need to get some sleep, or I'll have a hangover the size of my balls tomorrow morning."\par
They both guffawed heartily, much to the chargrin of the few pedestrians within earshot. They jumped in the car and, with one gigantic rev of the engine, sped off toward home.\par
\par
***********************************\par
\par
Home, of course, being the castle. It was lavish beyond all description, located right outside the city. Larry and Roy cut what should have been a thirty-minute drive down to ten as the elder of the two cut corners like a maniac and sped like he was placing in the Indy qualifyings. They passed several police cars on the way back to the Koopa compound, but none dared even turn on their lights, let alone give chase. They all knew.\par
And for every inch that Larry and Roy were given, they took a mile, and were never even called down. All of the Koopa kids did, though none took advantage of their bloodline as much as those two. It was difficult to say exactly where they had gone wrong; all of the children were bad seeds in one way or another. But no one could match the partying, substance abuse and living life on the edge that characterized every day of Larry and Roy's existence. Morton dealt with similar problems in alcohol, though his more meek and "loner" personality kept him from the bigger trouble, and the infamy that inevitably followed. Bowser, Iggy, Wendy, Ludwig and Lemmy were all witness to their siblings' grandoise sins almost constantly whenever they were around, but rarely did or said anything to remedy it. In the years that it had gradually worsened, they had grown to accept it as a part of their brothers' existence, and were afraid that if they confronted them on it, it would drive them away even further than they had already drifted. Their once-close-knit family had been dealt huge blows by the early loss of their mother, complicated by Bowser's and their own failure to subdue Mario's periodic but certain conquests, and only hurt further by the awkwardness of their entrance into adolescence, and the confusion and peer pressure that's interwoven into any teenage life, let alone influential royalty. To say that they were not as they were a decade prior would be a gross understataement... In all traditional definitions one could hardly call them a family anymore.\par
But they all held one thing in common... An intense dislike for Mario and all that followed him. Whether or not they were ever fully aware of it, he was a large part of their entropy; a huge piece of the puzzle surrounding their weak and deteriorating relationship. And they all knew that, come hell or high water, if he ever dared show his face on the stoop of the castle gates, they would all be there acting as one to bring him down and restore order. And perhaps then, they would find the common ground to once again feel like they belonged.\par
But unless and until that happened, they remained largely seperate, leading individual lives and only stopping in with one another on occasion, to exchange a few words or, in Larry and Roy's case, cause trouble.\par
The new moon was out tonight, and it was uncommonly dark when Roy pulled his car into the castle garage and swaggered in alongside Larry. As it was so late, no one was awake to notice them slink in and quietly go to their rooms to sleep away what little night remained.\par
\par
