"...F-f-fuck."\par
Larry awoke to the sound of his eldest brother, Ludwig, playing a passage from Rhapsody On A Theme Of Paganini. The Koopa kids' bedrooms shouldered up against the grand ballroom and the grand piano contained therein, so Ludwig's serenade was more than sufficient to wake Larry and make him aware of his crippling hangover. Not surprisingly, Larry had neither a knowledge of or appreciation for classical music, and on top of that, his peaked condition only made each note sound like it was being pounded into his brain. It was so overbearing, it took several moments for him to gather the strength to sit up and shout.\par
"STOP PLAYING THE MOTHER-FUCKIN' PIANO, FOR THE LOVE OF GOD!!!"\par
His own yelling wreaked havok on his headache. The pain was so intense that he couldn't even tell that Ludwig had immediately stopped, and was equally ignorant of his footsteps coming down the hall. He was just about to lean up and yell again for Ludwig to stop when his squinting eyes caught sight of the classical Koopa leaning into the threshold of his bedroom door.\par
"You asshole, you know I practice at dis time every day."\par
Larry's reply was delayed and uncharacteristically meek. "You don't practice until three in the fucking afternoon, and you know it."\par
"It EEZ three in ze fu- In ze afternoon."\par
Ludwig hated to curse, as did Wendy and Iggy. In the entire household, they were alone in sharing that.\par
Larry bolted up with a wincing scowl. The pain was unbearable, worse than any hangover he had ever had before.\par
"God damnit", he muttered, barely loud enough for Ludwig to hear. "I slept in without meanin' to and I STILL feel like fuckin' roadkill."\par
"You look like it, too." Ludwig's smart-assed reply would normally have made Larry try to punch him, but they both knew that Larry was in no condition to lash out at anyone. "Vat did you do zis time to kick your own ass?"\par
Larry sighed. "Two dime rocks, a blunt of high-grade herb, and a whole bottle of Everclear. And probably something else I can't fucking remember."\par
Ludwig rolled his eyes. "You're determined to kill yourself, aren't you? At least Roy paces himself."\par
Larry growled at him. Roy was pretty much his best friend, and he hated to hear his other siblings speak highly of him when he himself was on the rocks. It made him feel like they were trying to turn he and Roy against each other.\par
"Anyvay, as stupid and reckless as you may be, you're still my little brother, so I can at least go get you something to dull the pain, though I'm sure nothing vill take it avay completely."\par
Larry nodded weakly. "I could go for some headache medicine."\par
Ludwig immediately turned and went to retrieve the medicine. Ordinarily, amongst all of Larry's many pet peeves, his biggest was being called someone's "little" anything, but as soon as he knew Ludwig would willingly bring back medicine, he wisely chose to ignore the unintentional slam.\par
While Ludwig was gone, Larry took the opportunity to gather his head as best he could. He was still in the clothes he had worn yesterday, him having been so tired and inebriated on several things the night before he hadn't the strength nor the presence of mind to undress before he had lost consciousness. This actually worked in his favour, as he still had the pack of cigarettes and a straw from the drinks he had consumed en masse at the bar he was probably never allowed in again after his little "talk" with the barkeep. He always kept the straw from any joint he patronized, and it was for this very reason, one none of his siblings knew about, even Roy.\par
He concealed both items in an easy-to-reach pouch in his jacket just as he heard Ludwig rounding the corner a feet from his doorway. Moments later, his very forgiving and thoughtful brother held in front of him two tablets of Tylenol, which he took without so much as a 'thank you'. Ludwig wasn't surprised at all, and left without saying another word. He knew he had already done more for Larry than he deserved.\par
Once Ludwig was gone, Larry gradually forced himself to stand up, and shuffled over to the door, shutting and locking it, wincing as he heard the deadbolt turn within the jamb. He shuffled back to his bed, sat on the edge, and still clenching the pills in one hand, pulled out both the straw and the cigarette pack and laid them down beside himself. He then produced a lighter, and sat that down beside him as well. Then, he picked the cigarette pack back up, and using meticulous care as to not tear the tinfoil lining, gently removed it from the pack, and folded the edges up into a bowl. From there, he laid the Tylenol in the middle of the newly-made tin tray, picked up the lighter, ignited it and held it to the pills until they began to burn. As soon as he saw the smoke, he quickly set down the lighter, picked up the straw and sucked up the smoke with it. He did this repeatedly, until there was little left of the intended headache remedy but black and grey ashes.\par
His headache was gone, but only because he could no longer feel his head.\par
For any ordinary person, the last thing they would want to do when in the depths of depravity that inevitably follow a lengthy bender would be to immediately jump back onto abuse of anything. But here Larry was, getting through the pain the only way he knew how... By doing something to completely distract himself.\par
As he sat there, his head swimming with the unique high that can only come from smoking pills, his few cogniscent thoughts seemed to be spelled out to him, as if he were reading them rather than thinking them.\par
"I hit rock bottom a long time ago. And I'm keeping myself there because I enjoy it. I have no job, no car, and the few friends I have are being sent to prison for half their lives or more because of the same shit I'm doing. And my royal blood can't guarantee immunity from anything forever. Sooner or later, the people that know about my vices will find a way around Dad's benevolent, open mind, and I'll be in an eight-by-ten cell, too. And the judge will do his or her best to throw the book at me, because of who I am. I have no life when I'm doing this shit, and if I keep on doing it the little life I have left will be worthless, either rotting in a cell or rotting from the hundreds of diseases the cheap floozies I keep knocking up could have. I've never even gotten myself tested. I could have gonorrhea. Or syphillis. Or even, God forbid, HIV. And I just sit back and laugh it up with my brother and the few guys I know that are still living a free life like me."\par
These realizations held so much power at that moment that he threw himself back on the bed and did something he hadn't done in a long time... Cry.\par
He was powerless to do anything but heave with each sob. Everything he had considered was absolutely true, and nobody could convince him of it more than his own sense of logic. In so many ways, he may have already made a deadly mistake. Whether it be somebody that wasn't as lucky as he was ratting him out to police, or a drug lord that could come to get revenge for the many debts he owed for all manner of drugs, or a sexually-transmitted killer that could have silently crept into his body with the last big-breasted bimbo that exchanged one of his bills for his own cheap pleasure.\par
Right then and there, he made a decision. Assuming he still had a chance, he would never allow himself to risk his own self-destruction again. He would quit alcohol, weed, crack, pills, acid and coke cold turkey, and never so much as sink a one into a dancer's loose G-string again. He knew that he had no choice, and even if he did, to choose anything else would be signing his own death warrant. The last few years had been one nonstop, directionless party, and it was one that had to end. As his eyes dried and his mind cleared, he was only aware of an emotion that had all but died within him; thankfulness. The thankfulness to still be alive, to have another chance, to see what he needed so badly to change on his own, before someone or something made it painfully and tragically clear.\par
Ignring the pain now on his own, he sat up, took the foil, and threw it in the trashbasket. He once again stood, this time to \b un\b0 lock the door. And instead of lying back down, as he wanted to so badly, he opened the door and stepped out, with a newfound purpose. Before anything else, he knew what he must do.\par
He needed to apologize. To alot of people. About alot of things.\par
And he immediately set out to contact and amass the six closest to him, and prove to them that he wanted to turn over a new leaf, and bring them back together as a family once again.\par
