\par
Wendy was beautiful.\par
At least, that was the concensus among the men that frequented the Le Baron steakhouse in the artsy section of town. For several months, she had earned every dime of her own money waiting tables at this upscale restaurant. She didn't ever need a job at all, of course, considering her family's money; she only worked because she liked the experience and had some appreciation for the atmosphere that surrounds any classy bistro when the lunch crowd is in full swing.\par
It was undeniable that she had a talent for wooing money out of any male patron. Give her five sentences to say to a man, and she could have his whole wallet. This is how the bratty demeanor she had as a child had carried over into adulthood; it merely transformed into a knack for manipulation.\par
It's not that she ever tried to appear to be easy, or was loose, by any means; but she could flirt with you so much you would swear she had fallen in love with you between the salad and the entree. And she did it in such a way that you could never tell she was even the least bit insincere. It was this gift that made her the envy of every female co-worker around her.\par
Despite this one vice, she was perhaps the most on-the-ball of all of the Koopa children, a stark contrast to the troublemaker she had been in grade school. In many ways the polar opposite of Larry, Roy and Morton, she had never taken a drink or done any type of recreational drug, she rarely cursed, if ever, and she even chipped in a portion of her checks to children's charities. If she could be considered attractive on the outside (most of her fair appearance could be owed to the makeup and hairstyles she used, not a natural beauty), she was moreso on the inside, and every single man from saint to lush that ever had the good fortune to be one of her tables was only too eager to let her know.\par
And she wasn't blind to the affection she received, either. In the time she had been employed there, she had counted one hundred and twenty-eight wandering eyes, seventy-five requests for a date, and six marriage proposals. And one of the latter was from a married man whose wife was in the lavatory at the time.\par
But as much as she enjoyed the attention, she had no intention of taking any man up on his innuendo. Only recently she had dated a man that seemed at first to be genuine and affectionate,  only to find out he was interested in nothing besides her money. His neglectfulness and greed finally caused her to break it off with him after a few months, but only after the damage had already been done. He had broken her heart, and made it impossible for her to enjoy the company of a man, at least at this point in her life. Though he had not mistreated her to the point of making her hardened against affection, she hadn't gotten over how uncaring he had been, and so the propositions she received only flew over her head and back out into the night with each consumed meal, each paid check.\par
The bistro was in the footprint of a large office building, and just down the block from it was the nail salon where her best friend Haley, a middle-class Koopa a year older than her, gave manicures and pedicures. When Wendy was on break they would often meet in the waiting area at the front of the boutique and talk about all manner of things, until Wendy had to clock back in. Her friend was genuinely beautiful, with long sandy brown hair that had a pronounced natural curl, and petite features that contrasted her well-developed busom. Wendy was jealous of her natural good looks, but as she had so much more money and power, she never minded too much. Had only one of them one or both of these qualities, the one with neither would undoubtedly have resented the other, but both girls had a unique blessing, and it was this that brought and kept them together.\par
At the same time that Larry had been at home deciding to steer his life in a better direction, she had just come on shift. Of course, she knew none of what had occured when he had awakened, and wouldn't until she returned no earlier than five o'clock that night. For the next few hours, she was in her element, and she weaved between tables with such grace that one could observe her and be reminded of ice skating.\par
She had good focus on her job, but every now and then, as she carried a pitcher of water through sections of seating or flipped open her writing pad to jot down a long order, her thoughts would drift away, often to the things that troubled her.\par
"I wonder if I should go by the grocery store on the way back to the house tonight and pick up some chicken salad. I could really go for a sandwich with that and some ham, or maybe some pimento loaf. I think the last time I had one was when Morton and me stayed up all night watching that marathon of Trading Spaces. Yeah, it must be, because that was when he had brought out that six-pack of King Cobra and was being a bit too loud."\par
She chuckled. When she thought about things like that, she often laughed to keep from crying. Just like Larry and Roy, Morton was never around. After Bowser had bought him that canary yellow Mustang a year prior, he had been gone most of the time, usually hopping between friends' houses until in the last few months he had moved away and severed all social ties entirely. Before that, It had not been unusual for him to leave and not come back for a month or more, and when he did, he was still buzzed from whatever he had consumed in his prolonged absence. When he was sober, he was quiet and somewhat antisocial, but when he was drunk, while it brought out his voice, it oddly served to only make him more of a loner. He could drink a few beers and then shut himself off in his room the rest of the night, watching television or just lying on his bed doing nothing but staring up at the ceiling.\par
Wendy was perhaps closest to him of all of the Koopa kids, and so she was usually the one that was with him when he decided to just spend the rest of the night alone. She never took it personally, as she realized it was only the way he was when he drank, but it saddened her to see him leave her side when they were just hanging out and usually having a good time doing all sorts of things to pass the time. She missed him more than she missed any other sibling when he wasn't there, and she hated the fact that he hadn't take more opportunities to spend time with her, before moving out and oddly never speaking to her or any of his brothers since. She disliked the weakness of her family so much that she couldn't stand to see the one person that still seemed to spend time with her choosing instead to ignore her. But she took it in stride as much as possible, and most nights she avoided feeling very sorry for herself, instead opting to try to get in touch with Lemmy, her other favourite brother, when she got home. Tonight was no exception, and as she pondered his recent absence while refilling a glass of tea, she decided to call him later on his cell phone. She didn't doubt she would be able to reach him, as she usually did, and he wasn't usually hesitant to end phone conversations with her.\par
The shift passed quickly for some reason that night, and as she hung up her apron on the wall next to kitchen, practically jogged out the front door, got in her purple Trans Am and headed towards home, she flipped open her phone and dialed him, reaching him after only two rings. She talked to him all the way to the castle about the little things that had happened during the day to both of them, and it was only after she was home and the car was parked that they finally finished talking and hung up. By then she was in the front door, and ready to head upstairs to her room and relax, especially after the usual bullshit she had to take in her service-industry job.\par
