As structured as Wendy liked to keep her life, Iggy was only moreso. Like all of the Koopalings save for her, he held no steady employment, but spent most of his free time pursuing his own hobbies. And the greatest of these, not surprisingly, was the science lab that he had built from the ground up in the castle basement. He had spent over a year on it, buying every single beaker, tube and compound himself, and spending huge amounts of the family fortune, much to the displeasure of Bowser, although he said nothing. But after liberal amounts of time, money, blood, sweat and tears, he had finally completed it in the past few weeks, and to him, it was well worth it.\par
To descend down the narrow, rickety staircase that led from the main hall to the lab was like entering another world entirely. Iggy's pride and joy was no smaller in space than a high school gym, and every few feet for the entire length of the facility were room-wide tables packed full of glass beakers, test tubes, formulas and solutions. Even in the low light of the few incandescent bulbs hanging from the ceiling, the entire room seemed to shimmer, as the glass reflected and magnified all of the light as well as the colours of each flask's contents. It was sometimes so intense that it rivaled the prismatic effects of a laser light show, albeit not changing or in motion at all.\par
Though the sheer amount of chemicals and mixed elements was nothing short of staggering, Iggy knew exactly what and where everything was. He had no assistants, save for Lemmy, who might come downstairs from time to time when he was home. He only ever intended to talk with Iggy and visit for a while, but the spectacled science prodigy inevitably had him do at least one or two things to help out each time they were together. Lemmy never minded, as he was Iggy's twin brother, and he would do everything short of die for him; but even for him, there was something slightly unsettling about Iggy's blind devotion to his craft, above all else in the world, even eating and sleeping.\par
Iggy had no good friends. It's not that he was a total dork or was bad at talking to people; he was actually quite adept at relating to others. He just chose to spend his time in his own version of an impenetrable fortress, tinkering with formulas and sundries from dawn until the wee hours of the next morning, stopping only for a short time during the day to rest, eat, or whatever else was necessary for him to keep going. He had only had the lab finished and running for a short time, so most of his experiments were still in the testing stages, but the few he had managed to complete sat on the long shelves against one side of the room, most untouched since they were first set there. He enjoyed the methods it took to make them and seeing them to completion more than he ever would actually using most of them for any of their intended purposes... Though they all had an objective or use, to Iggy, it was somehow lost in translation from the bottles to the finished product.\par
And the compounds he toiled away at creating were never similar at all from one to the next; he might make a sweet, edible drink one day and a corrosive superacid strong enough to melt glass the next. He had never needed anyone to school him on the proper way to handle hazardous materials. He had never slipped up and spilled something, or foregone the proper safety produres in his rush to see something to completion... His talents for all facets of the craft were simply amazing.\par
The thing was, they were amazing only to him. No one besides his family ever knew of his whereabouts, let alone this huge underground haven of chemistry, and while they realized how complicated most of it was and appreciated his devotion, they seldom enjoyed to participate. Science was in Iggy's blood, and none of theirs.\par
But they never despised him for it, or even joked about it at all. He was blessed in that they understood how important it was to him, and respectfully allowed him the room they were sure he wanted. And every now and then, they knew he would have to emerge from the bowels of the castle to consume and rest. And when he did, he was always met by at least a few of them, and they enjoyed his company for the entire time he was awake and above his own little world, until he inevitably said good-bye, closed the creaky basement door and was unavailible once again.\par
Just a few days after he had put the final beaker in place, he had even invited the whole lot down to help him celebrate its completion, and all accepted. It literally took hours for him to show them around every nook and cranny of his space-age play room, a tour he was only too happy to give. For the most part, they only followed and listened to his descriptions of things they knew nothing about, occasionally stopping to gaze into a particularly odd-looking formula or marvel at the geometric complication within the tubes that connected glass to glass. Larry had even joked that if Iggy would rent him out some space down there, he would like to make meth and sell it for them to split the profits. Iggy laughed, but told him on no uncertain terms that wasn't happening. Bowser was also along on the tour, but stayed at the back and never seemed too happy or interested with anything. Though he would never say anything for fear of crushing Iggy's spirit, he had always expected his most technically gifted son to become a world-famous scientist and devise cures for all manner of terrible diseases, not while away his hours and talents with an innumerable number of side projects that never saw the light of day. But, he conceded that it was Iggy's choice to do what he wanted in life and not his own, so he left well enough alone, though after that day they seldom spoke, even during the short visits he had with Wendy, Larry, Roy, Ludwig, Morton and/or Lemmy.\par
And that's the way it was, day in and day out, from one project to the next in a seamless, almost graceful cycle that was without end or higher purpose. Iggy's pure white lab coats became his only wardrobe, and he was never seen without them, even when asleep. The two he owned were cycled out every day as Wendy took care of the family's laundry, and should he ever find the one on him becoming dirty, he could always count on her to have hung the other, clean one on the other side of the basement door at the foot of the stairs. He, like everyone else, recognized how much she did for all of them, and whenever they spoke he never failed to remind her of his appreciation for that and for never giving him a hard time for his reclusive nature. He realized how odd his hermit tendancies must be to her and his other siblings, but he also knew that he was so genuinely married to his work that it was impossible for him to change.\par
Iggy loved his life, his family and his craft, and nothing else, and was content with that much. His mind and love were incredibly complex, but his needs were simple. And though none of his brethren ever fully understood the world he lived in, they respected him, for being something they knew they could never be.\par
