Lemmy, on the other hand, was as different in demeanor from Iggy as he was similar in looks. Being twins, they had the same features, but Lemmy's lack of spectacles, along with his more contemporary style, made them appear so radically different they hardly seemed like twins, or even brothers.\par
Lemmy had long, straight hair that came down to his shoulders and often draped over the back of his threadbare Die Hard T-shirt, which was older than one of his friends. He was always in shorts, even during the dead of winter when everyone else was bundled up in several layers.\par
Lemmy was a skater, pure and simple. He had picked up his first board when he was six, and in the fifteen years since had honed his skills until he was nothing short of a pro. In fact, he was rarely seen off of his treasured four wheels, whether he was at home doing tricks and grinds off of ramps and rails he set up himself, or riding through the city streets with three or four buddies. Of all of the Koopa kids, you were most likely to see him no matter where you were. He had a knack for showing up in the most unexpected places, ollying whatever low objects were around, then simply riding off. He and the skating entourage he kept company with constantly would do everything from grind down escalator rails in the mall to 360 Indy Kickflip over the awning of a barner shop, talking and laughing the whole time as if they were the only people in the world.\par
But as random and sometimes illegal as their presence was, there were few who minded. They were street legends among the kids, and older people considered it good luck to see them pass by, for some reason or another. Anytime Lemmy or one of his friends performed some technical stunt, they were often met by cheers from high school kids, and even some adults who appreciated the dedication it took for them to get as good at riding as they had gotten. But Lemmy never acknowledged his admirers nor his critics, and only kept riding.\par
He was rarely seen without his buddies. His best friend, Todd, was built like a brick wall and half a head taller than Roy. He was always directly behind him, often following Lemmy's lead or sometimes doing the exact opposite thing to attract attention from onlookers. He had never smoked a single cigarette, but always carried a minibottle of some sort of liqueur, and if Lemmy ever stopped to rest, it was usually in front of the ABC store so Todd could go in and pick up another one. He always bought one at a time, and never consumed enough to even feel a buzz. It was anyone's guess why he even bothered to drink hard liqueur if he never drank enough to get plastered. Most speculated that he liked the taste of alcohol, or maybe that he really was drunk, but was such a good skater you could never tell.\par
Behind Todd was usually sixteen-year-old Bret, whom Lemmy affectionately called Little B. He was no more than five feet, three inches tall, but he could ride faster and jump higher than any of them. But the one thing he could not do was grind. He had never boardslid across anything, not a railing, not a ledge, not even for a fraction of a second. He could never bring himself to try, and neither Lemmy nor Todd ever urged him to. So, if they both slid down a stairway rail, he would jump the steps instead. And he had never fallen, or over or undershot the bottom.\par
Last in line was Walt. While the rest of them rode pretty much every single day, he was only with them on weekends. He was taller than Little B at five-feet six, but was four years younger than him and still in middle school. He never performed any tricks other than a manual, which he could hold almost indefinitely. It wasn't out of the question to see him up on two wheels the whole day, following behind his older friends and watching them do the more technical stunts. He didn't say much, but when he did, it was usually to tell them a joke or something that had happened during the week at school. They could appreciate his stories because it reminded them of their younger days, and what they had been doing at his age.\par
And that's the way they were always seen, anywhere and everywhere. Often, you could be walking through the park, or leaving a restaurant, and you would see them, Lemmy out in front, laughing at something Walt had said about some teacher or a female student, Todd behind him, ollying when and where he did, Little B swerving almost impossibly sharply so as not to fly right by them, and Walt up on his back wheels just following.\par
Lemmy had an unspoken girlfriend. She had appeared beside him one day when they had all rounded the corner of a building, on her own board and keeping up with them quite well, with her long brown ponytail blowing in the wind and sometimes hitting the back of the sparkly blue belly T-shirt above her low-rise jeans. They watched her as she weaved inbetween them, working her way up from the back of the pack until she was beside Lemmy. None of the five said said anything, and she stayed beside him for tens of blocks, neither she nor Lemmy looking at each other, until she veered off at an intersection.\par
After that, she appeared in the same way without warning at least once a day, and never said a word, nor did she and Lemmy exchange glances. It was anyone's guess whether or not in the three months that this had been occurring, they had actually even seen each other, despite the fact that when she rode with him she was no more than a foot away. Within the first two weeks, he had started referring to her as his "girlfriend", and when he would talk about her to the other guys or to his family, he would say he hoped to "see my girl today." It was the perhaps the most unorthodox relationship anyone had ever seen, if it could even be called such, and it was as much a legend in the streets as Lemmy and his crew themselves.\par
Lemmy's only worldly posessions were his clothes and his board. His first set of wheels was blank and nameless, and had lasted him ten of his fifteen years skating, and on his sixteenth birthday Bowser gave him the only gift he knew his son would appreciate... A navy blue Birdhouse and a can of spray paint to put whatever design he wanted on the bottom. Lemmy had given the can to each of the other Koopalings, then to his buddies, and they all sprayed on their initials. He said he wanted them to so he would always have part of them with him, wherever he went. And he silently vowed to one day have his unspoken love put her whole name on, provided he ever talked to her.\par
Like so many of his siblings, the skating prince was rarely at home, so little that it wouldn't surprise anyone he knew if he slept on his board going fifteen miles an hour. If he stopped in with Iggy, it was the only time he was without his friends, and it was never long before he was back out on the streets or on the course he had built behind the castle. Lemmy had even said that, when he died, he wanted to set up a ramp on the roof of the castle and jump down to the ground. That was the way he wanted to go out, and nobody could convince him otherwise. And Todd, Little B and Walt had all said that if he did, they would be right behind him, though none of them really intended to go through with it.\par
So, though the twins were radically different in so many ways, they shared one characteristic, and that was that their passions were few, simple and constantly being fulfilled.\par
