Sophistication was Ludwig's middle name, and the hallmark of the eldest Koopaling.\par
All through childhood and into adulthood, he was hailed as a genius in studies and a child prodigy on the piano. And his love for both had never faded after the praise had stopped when it started to become expected of him by others, and when he grew too old to get compliments from everyone automatically. The praise for his talents had never gone to his head so much that he believed himself better than everyone else, but it did help to instill a generous portion of self-confidence, just enough to be annoying to some but refreshing to others, depending on how they interpreted it. And Ludwig never went a day without his piano; he loved it like it was his own spawn, and it became the outlet for the majority of his creativity and spirit, an avenue from which he could paint all manner of pictures and convey every imaginable emotion, with just a few strokes of the ivory keys. Through the years, he had grown to accept it as an extension of himself, a part of him that held his innermost thoughts and desires, and he often felt it was the only thing capable of expressing these thoughts to a world only too eager to listen to its commanding fluorishes and soothing serenades, made possible by the skill and steady hand that had blossomed like a babied flower under the rigorous regimens of practice he disciplined himself to not only engage in, but thoroughly enjoy as well. Perhaps it was in the family's blood to tend to have one or two great loves in life... Whether it was or not, he wasn't an exception.\par
Ludwig was the only Koopaling that had yet attained any post-high school education, Bowser having sent him to Barenstone, a 4-year school for the academically and musically gifted, which he graduated from with honours a year prior no more than a month from his twenty-third birthday. And not surprisingly, given his age, he was the first of Bowser's children to wed.\par
His wife of two years, Esmerelda, was far less of a witch than her name would lead anyone to believe. She was, in fact, a beautiful and loving woman, and was admired by all of the Koopa clan. She was the daughter of the most wealthy family in Grand Koopa City (Her father owned an oil company on the prestigious South side of town), and she was rarely seen without a lavish, flowing dress and copious amounts of fine jewelry on her hands, ears and neck. Seeing as how both she and Ludwig were well-to-do, many commoners thought it to be an arranged marriage, borne of the pride of two upstanding bloodlines; however, it was their decision alone to wed, not their parents' or any piece of paper's. They had met, fallen in love and become engaged while both attended Barenstone. Often, after school was concluded for the day, Ludwig would get permission from the headmaster to remain there for a few hours to practice, and he and Esmerelda would while away the hours in the classroom where Ludwig studied and advanced his skill in piano. He would play something striking and classic like Prelude in C or Intermezzo, while her operatically trained voice would accompany it with the majestic stacatto and intense emotion that characterized her style. Should they be there immediately following class hours and no later, those that still remained within earshot were treated to the grand and beautiful duet of their undeniable talents, and they were often approached afterwards by those that had no problem with telling them that they were too talented to still be there and not out at Carnegie Hall. Hearing any praise, Ludwig would thank whomever may be complimenting them, and Esmerelda, having been brought up to be very humble and ladylike, would only smile and turn away bashfully.\par
It had been only a season's lapse from their coinciding graduation dates when they had gone to the altar and been forever joined in marital bliss, and Bowser, immensely pleased at the wife his eldest son had attained, expected to immediately be blessed with the pitter-patter of little footsteps around the castle.\par
But it was not to be. Esmerelda was a wonderful and caring wife to Ludwig, but she had one failing that was impossible to remedy.\par
She was barren. \par
Despite her being perfect in almost every other way, she was incapable of carrying Ludwig's children. Ludwig, being a kind and understanding issue, never felt contempt for her because of it or believed her to have failed him in any way. He knew it could not be helped, and only comforted her as her eyes misted whenever they might be out and see a baby carriage, or walk by a stuffed bear in a luxury department store. She was far more hurt by her limitation than he could ever be; it was almost as if she carried the pride of both of them, and was doubly crushed by the curse she knew she must've inherited from her mother. She had been the only one of eight births that had survived more than a few hours after delivery, and she was sure that this is how her mother's tragic difficulties in childbirth had manifested itself in her own generation. But, she often thought to herself, at least my mother had carried so many times, and finally had me. I will never even reach that point, no matter how long I may live.\par
Despite often hating her one flaw, most other times she took it in stride, and realized it for what it was, no more than a chance anatomical anomaly that probably saved her unbelievable pain she knew nothing about. And, as she slowly grew to accept it, she and Ludwig were blessed by the love they both shared for each other, and the wonderful feeling that came with just being together. And she knew, if the time ever came that he grew discontent with having no one to carry on his name, they could adopt. She was sure he would not be a father so prideful that he would refuse to raise someone else's child, like so many men that she knew she could've fallen in love with instead, had the fates not been kind to her, at least in love, if not childbearing.\par
But still, they had always been content so far, and if Ludwig had ever felt the need to raise a child, he hadn't spoken of it yet. Bowser, having grown quite fond of his daughter-in-law (in an exclusively plutonic way), had given her and Ludwig the fabulous, unoccupied guest bedroom in the tallest tower of the castle, to be their own lavish home within a home. It was so richly furnished and exclusive that none besides Bowser or his children had ever even laid eyes upon the wonders it contained, everything from a posh marble fountain to a bed with sheets made of the finest Mongolian silk, so expensive that to obtain it Bowser had spent enough to buy a mansion in Grand Koopa City as palatial as Esmerelda's family owned, and perhaps more. Ludwig and Esmerelda's life was often said to be the finest and most happy in all of the kingdom, mostly from townsfolk that only thought so because of their own jealousy for any life of priveledge.\par
And against all odds, the fabulous life they indeed shared never eroded their respectively humble natures, or the thankfulness that was uncommon for any royalty. Instead of needlessly hoarding their blessings or feeling contempt for those that were below them in class, at their request the grand ballroom in the lower part of the castle was often filled with guests of all means and social classes, not excluding the poor and destitute, many of whom would never have so much as seen a single brick in the castle's outer walls were it not for Ludwig's coaxing his father to allow them entrance and high times among the castle's most well-to-do. Ludwig often felt sorry for those that hadn't had the blessings that he always had, and thus was the motivation behind his tendancies to mingle with them as well as his own peers. Bowser would never have allowed such people to grace his abode had it not been for Ludwig's own accomplishments and the pride it instilled in his father's stoic and often cold heart.\par
But as much as Esmerelda loved her husband and the way he never looked down on or excluded anyone when social gatherings took place, she never had felt comfortable around his brothers and sister.\par
It's not that she felt that their awkward and sometimes odd behaviour was unsettling, or that they had ever shown any contempt or dislike for her in word or action... But being around them somehow only served to remind her of her inability to carry, and whether or not any of them had ever held disdain for her because of it, she always felt that they did. They must, she thought. It must bother them to know that their eldest and most gifted brother will never have the chance to pass on his talents to a son or daughter.\par
And it was because of these errant doubts and self-convincings that she seldom was seen away from their lavish chambers atop the castle, whenever any of Ludwig's younger siblings were to be found there. And Ludwig, perhaps knowing why she chose to avoid his own flesh and blood, never pressed the issue. He loved and respected her far too much to make her face something or someone she had no desire to.\par
And so, though he was often within the castle's walls, if he was sharing his time with Wendy, Lemmy or whomever else might be home at the time and not within the room Bowser had gifted unto him and his lovely bride, he was always without her.\par
