The only word that could be used to accurately describe Morton would be loner.\par
Since he had moved out of the castle, he never kept company of any kind, for any amount of time, no matter what he might be doing. He detested socializing of any kind, and was alays quick to avoid talking to anyone if he could get out of it.\par
Iggy's tendancies to forego friendships were totally involuntary, and only due to the fact that his hobby never included others, save for his own family. Morton was different.\par
He made a conscious decision to avoid anyone and everyone that crossed his path, with one exception.\par
Even the job he had was tailored to his quirk. He sorted and filed papers for an insurance company, where he worked with nothing more than pages and print all day. When he clocked out every evening, he went straight back to his one-bedroom flat on the Upper East side of Grand Koopa City, never stopping to linger anywhere he didn't absolutely need to be.\par
He was the only Koopaling that no longer lived at home. He had moved out four months prior, befuddling Bowser by choosing to give up his share of the family fortune and live in poverty. He didn't make much from his work; the checks he brought home barely made utilities, food, alcohol and his half of a two-way split rent. He didn't even have basic cable, and he took the bus to work every day in place of buying a car.\par
None of his family had seen him in the months since he had left. It's not that they didn't want to, or didn't know where he was... He had given them express instructions not to come see him, and when they had asked why, he only said he was always busy and didn't have the time to visit with them. And they couldn't call him, because he didn't own a phone.\par
It was he and he alone that knew why he chose to live out his life without them, and it was all due to the fact that there was one person that he didn't avoid.\par
When Morton was born, he was a difficult birth. Bowser's late wife had been in labour with him for thirty-nine hours when the doctors finally pulled him from the birth canal, and his mother was so tired and spent from her difficult delivery that she immediately fell unconscious. Thus, it was Bowser himself who in the delivery room first spotted Morton's unusual birthmark, the star over his right eye, and took it to be such a good omen for the rest of his new life that he gave the child the highest honour he could think of: naming him after his grandfather and Bowser's father, Morton Koopa senior.\par
But with Bowser's favour came great expectations that Morton often found difficult to meet. Bowser wanted him to be the smartest student in school, the strongest and fastest athlete on the gym team, the most talented musician of those of his kids that had any musical ability, and so on and so on. Morton, despite his being very good at all of these things, occasionally slipped up in one or the other, but when he did, Bowser was never understanding. He needlessly and cruelly berated Morton for his failings, even when his overall performance wasn't bad at all, just not the best among his peers. The friends he had and used to be close to all through early school life began to drift away as Morton was forced to spend all of his spare time studying and working out just to ensure that he could outpace his competition enough to keep his father off of his back. And this continued well through adolescence, as Morton, despite his being next to youngest of the Koopa kids and much to his chargrin, was also unbenevolently informed that he was expected to bring home a girl before any of his brothers, to carry on the family name.\par
But of all of the things expected of him from his father, this was the only one he knew he could not do.\par
Three years prior, shortly after his seventeenth birthday, he had begun to take a particular interest in a rather well-built classmate by the name of Tom. Even though his age was no more than Morton's he was already six feet in height and it was rumoured could benchpress well over a thousand pounds. Tom sat directly in front of Morton in first-period English, and though he didn't yet know why he often found himself staring at the intimidating koopa's well-developed biceps instead of concentrating on his own schoolwork. This, of course, made his grades suffer, which was the source of considerably more anger from Bowser, and they only suffered more when Morton found out the location of the gym where Tom worked out, and began spending most of his free time there whenever he knew Tom was going to be toning up, instead of at home doing homework.\par
One day, when they were both using weight machines across from each other, Morton finally got up the nerve to stop, approach him and introduce himself. His greetings were met with a smile, and they soon got to talking, something Morton had been missing dearly since his social life had begun to go downhill seemingly so long ago. One subject led to another, and in the span of about an hour Morton found out alot about Tom, and about himself. And after they exhausted all of the subject matter they cared to discuss, Morton led Tom to a stall in the far corner of the gym's restroom and allowed the muscular Koopa to take his innocence.\par
And thus began a whirlwind romance behind the backs of Bowser and all of the rest of the family. Morton's grades rarely climbed above D or D-, as he spent every evening at his new boyfriend's apartment on the Upper East side, where they usually talked, ate dinner and then did all manner of things he knew his father would never understand nor accept. To Morton, these evenings were his whole day, and the rest was only so much black-and-white fuzz, a necessary bane that he could not face his father without.\par
But despite his newfound happiness with Tom, Bowser's stern, unfeeling criticism took its toll with every curse and empty ultimatum. Morton held out only until he could graduate high school, then immediately found a steady job, packed up all of his possesions and left with nothing more than a muttered, unfeeling "good-bye".\par
He moved in with Tom, whose job was no longer adequate to support the rising cost of living without someone else's income, and ever since had lived with the only one he felt understood and accepted him for who he was.\par
It was a match made in heaven. Tom was waiting for him after his bus pulled up at the apartment building every day without fail, and after a strong and heartfelt embrace they walked up the steps together and spent hours sipping wine and lying in each other's arms, sometimes talking about how many stacks of files Morton had organized that day, or how much of a house Tom had built on his framing crew. Often, though, they said nothing, only silently enjoying each other's company and the relaxing effect of the wine at the end of a stressful day. Though Tom made a good amount as skilled labour, they lived simply, saving up money for the day when they would finally be able to afford a nice house out in the country somewhere, a place they would no longer be bothered by anyone. Their decision for social exclusion was mutual, and driven by both their hatred for their unaccepting families and the knowledge that no one else would likely ever understand, either.\par
Larry probably missed Morton most of all. They similarly held contempt for the way the rest of the family treated them and chided their respective vices, and thus were very close before Morton had moved away and severed all ties. They used to spend hours after the sun set downing beers and shots and playing fighting games, and it seemed to Larry that Morton understood that he was not like their Dad, or the rest of them that would criticize whatever Bowser didn't, especially his alcohol problem. So when Morton left abruptly and without explanation, Larry felt betrayed, like he had somehow been grouped in with the rest of them. It was something he hadn't gotten over yet, and was a big part of his hitting rock bottom shortly after with substance abuse and staying out at all hours of the night. He didn't suspect Morton of being gay, otherwise, he might've put two and two together and decided it was better for Morton to have his own life. He only stewed over his older brother's absence and felt heartache at the same time, the emotions usually mixed with and dulled by all manner of unnatural drugs. And through it all, he patiently waited for Morton to come back, a hope he only held stronger with his now-decision to clean up. And more than any of the other siblings he was determined to reunite, he felt the need to contact Morton, and restore their unspoken alliance once again.\par
He knew that, of all people Morton would be the first to ever accept his apology and welcome him and hopefully everyone else back into his family.\par
But even though Morton missed him just as much, and would most likely return to the castle only for him, it was anyone's guess as to whether or not he could ever forgive his father for the relentless brow-beating he had endured for years, or his siblings for not doing anything to stop it, and even joining in from time to time.\par
It was lucky that Larry knew where Morton lived; everyone else could be contacted easily, but Larry, at this point still in his room and just about to leave, knew he had to go get him in person. And it was probably better this way, he thought, as he stepped out, pulled out his phone and first called Lemmy, then Roy, then Ludwig, knowing Wendy and Iggy would be home that night regardless. The black Harley-Davidson he rarely pulled out of the garage was running smoothly as he talked to all three of them, only telling them what he knew would get them all home and together that night. He would save revealing the actual reason why for when they were all together. \par
His conversation with Ludwig had just ended when he pulled up beside the door to Morton and Tom's apartment. As it was close to four in the afternoon, Morton had just gotten home, so to Larry's benefit he was still completely sober when his footsteps resounded, immediately preceeding his opening the door to a face he hadn't seen in a long time. It was only because it was Larry and no one else that he didn't immediately close it again, but only looked at his youngest brother with confusion as he spoke.\par
"What are you doing here?", he said, his voice showing mild but unmistakeable frustration. "I told you when I moved away that I wasn't coming back."\par
Larry smiled, in a way that he hadn't in a long time. "There's nothing that says I can't visit you."\par
"Except me", Morton answered flatly, and was just about to shut the door when Larry interjected.\par
"-Wait, wait, there's something I need to tell you." He was beginning to sweat; Morton obviously didn't want to talk to him, and he had to think of something to get Morton home without reveling why. "It's... Uh... I mean, I... Ummm..."\par
"Okay, that's very interesting, but I have to go now. Bye."\par
"WAIT! It's... DAD!! Yeah, it's Dad! He says he's sorry about the way he rode your ass all through your childhood, and he wants to apologize and for you to come back."\par
Though Morton didn't exactly appreciate Larry's choice of words, he said nothing about it as he laened against the door frame. This was a good sign, Larry thought. It proves he's not going to shut it on me.\par
"So, Dad finally admitted he's wrong.", Morton said, sounding relieved.\par
"Absolutely", Larry lied, feeling terrible about it. "He said he'll never put you through that shit again, as long as he lives."\par
Morton shook his head. "Hopefully, he won't live that much longer."\par
Larry's countenance fell, anticipating Morton to deny his request. But against all odds, the closeted Koopaling smiled, and replied with seemingly newfound vigor. "Alright, he talked you into talking me into it. Let me get a few of my things and say some goodbyes, and I'll be ready." Morton didn't intend to return permanently by any means, but only to stay for a few hours, just enough time to catch up with everyone. His place was with Tom now, and he knew it.\par
Larry's eyebrow raised with Morton's words. "I thought you lived alone. Who do you need to say goodbye to?"\par
Morton's smile faded; he knew he had said too much. "Uh, just some people from work."\par
"Yeah, right", Larry replied, not as easy to fool as Morton. "Well, I don't care who's here with you right now, just say your goodbyes and come on. Everybody should be- I mean, IS waiting for us."\par
Morton nodded, and gently slinked back inside the door. Larry heard unplaceable muffled voices and what sounded like a kiss before Morton returned to the door, a change of clothes in hand, and shut it behind him. Larry decided not to ask him about who it was; that, he would save for later, if all went well.\par
Larry hopped on the Harley, Morton (being unaccustomed to riding motorcycles of any kind) awkwardly positioned himself behind him, and they sped off towards home, with Morton's head full of lies and Larry's full of silent prayers that all hell wouldn't break loose when the truth was revealed.\par
