\par
Meanwhile, back at the castle, Wendy had just returned home from her shift. As she climbed the grand staircase and rounded the corner to the hallway that led to all of the siblings' bedrooms, she was surprised to Larry standing next to her door, and in perfectly decent street clothes, at that. Moreover, as she observed his mannerisms for a few seconds, it became apparent that he was completely sober. She didn't speak to him until she had slowly walked up and past him into her bedroom and set down her purse on the vanity across from her bed. It wasn't that she didn't have a million questions to ask him; but Larry was known to be unpredictable, and once he had even pulled a knife on her to try to extort money for drugs, so she was understandably cautious. Once she saw that he was up to nothing, though, she didn't hesitate to start talking.\par
"What are you doing outside my door?", she asked as she casually strolled up to him with her hands on her hips. "Looking for something to steal?"\par
"No, sis." His eyes were clear and somewhat apologetic as he replied. "I was waiting for you. We need to talk."\par
She crossed her arms. "Yeah, we do, now that you look like you're not out of your mind on some sort of chemical."\par
He nodded weakly and looked down at the floor, clearly feeling shame. "Come on. Everyone else is here and waiting for us in the foyer."\par
She raised her eyebrow. "Everyone meaning who? And why are they waiting on us?"\par
"Roy, Morton, Iggy, Lemmy and Ludwig. I told them to meet us there because I have something important to tell you and them. And it's something I'd rather you all hear at once."\par
\par
Begrudgingly, Wendy allowed Larry to lead her into the inner foyer of the castle, perhaps the simplest room with the palatial residence's four walls. It housed only a few simple couches and light fixtures, and was only made for rest and silence, a haven for anyone within the stately domain that could appreciate solace and the absence of distractions. Larry felt it was the perfect place to let the cat out of the bag; should there be a fallout of any kind, it would, at least for the time being, be contained, and not immediately spread by word of mouth throughout the castle and ultimately the kingdom.\par
All of the other five Koopalings had taken seats, the two couches almost devoid of any more room. Iggy and Lemmy sat beside each other and Roy on one, talking between themselves freely as if they belonged there, though neither ever took advantage of their present location, or most other places within the castle for that matter. Perhaps more surprising than their being in that room and not occupied with their respective hobbies was Lemmy's being there alone. None of his entourage had entered the castle with him after he had been called and asked to come by Larry, and at that moment they were in the backyard taking advantage of the concrete ramps and iron rails that were abundant in the course Lemmy had seen built by the best construction crews in Bowser's jurisdiction. Though the twins were smiling and talking freely, Roy was not. He wasn't too fond of being forced to sit with them and not Morton (whom he felt he had more in common with), and remained silent throughout their conversation, only leaning his head back on the soft collar of his jacket and staring up at the ceiling as if in a trance. He basically was, though, as none of the other Koopalings were unaware of the strong scent of weed that emanated from his general area. None minded, though; Roy had been smoking for far longer than Larry had been doing anything, so they were used to that smell, and understood that among all of the things Roy and Larry did, it was perhaps the most benign.\par
On the other couch, Ludwig and Morton sat, both silent. Ludwig was busy planning a garden ball for the next week at the request of Esmerelda, who felt that their extravagant gatherings would benefit from being outdoors for a change, as the weather had been fair for many days on end, and was not expected to turn sour anytime soon. Morton had no motivation besides secrecy for his lack of vocalizing, save perhaps for his missing Tom, who had, of course, stayed behind at the apartment, knowing how unwelcome his presence would be at Morton's past home, especially if the truth were ever revealed.\par
It was clear that they did not all see eye to eye, though that was due to many things other than just their differences. It was this that Larry knew to be true and was counting on, as he was also aware that whatever reaction they had to his getting back on the straight and narrow, whether it be happiness, skepticism or perhaps something entirely different, would most likely be in unison. And having them all agree on something would be the first step in bringing them back together as a family, which he so desperately wanted, especially since he was already feeling something he hadn't counted on: The horrible pangs of someone addicted to many substances, each one invariably tearing at his mind and body until they got another fix, and were quieted once more. It was hell facing withdrawal, and Larry knew that getting through it would require support that was near-impossible if his family remained seperated.\par
Neither their positions nor actions had changed as the jamb of the small door at one end of the otherwise closed-off room clicked and the door itself swung slowly open. All eyes were on Larry as soon as he appeared behind it, as it was obvious to all of them that he was not presently high on anything. They hadn't seen him that way in quite a while, and their mouths were all silent as they marveled at this fact.\par
"My brothers", Larry begun, almost unable to look at them because of the intense shame he felt, "You no doubt are aware that I called you all for a reason, though none of you know what it is yet." Wendy, who had been behind him and unseen by the rest, now stepped out into view, and seeing her there along with everyone else let them know how important this must be. "Well, I'm sure by now you've noticed something about me, and I'll let one of you tell me what it is before I continue."\par
Roy was the one who piped up. "You're not drunk or high at all." His voice, unlike any of the others, sounded disappointed. He knew that he and Larry were essentially of the same mind, and to see Larry possibly changed was disconcerting for many reasons.\par
Larry meekly smiled. "I can tell you're not happy about it, Roy, but yes, you're exactly right. Something happened in that room today that let me know just how far I'd slipped, and that I needed to come clean. But," he continued as he stepped into the room and allowed his gaze to pass over every one of their faces, "It reminded me of something else. Something I know we're all familiar with, but probably never think about anymore."\par
Wendy was the only one that had already caught on to what he was about to say, and her eyes welled up with tears. She now knew she was not the only one that felt as she did.\par
"Remember,", Larry said as he himself began to get choked up, "the glory days? Years ago, when we were still a family, and we spent all sorts of time together doing whatever came to our minds and loving every minute of it, just because, even with us being kids, we knew that we were all in it together? That we were there for each other, that we could face Mario, or whomever or whatever else, because we were there for each other?"\par
Everyone, though transfixed, remained silent, so he continued, his voice breaking up more and more as the power of the emotion swept over him in waves.\par
"Roy," he continued, almost in tears, "Remember when you and Lemmy stayed up all night eating Krunchers and watching movies you both knew you were much too young for?"\par
Roy thought a moment, and laughed slightly. "Yeah, I do! That night, I remember we watched \i A Clockwork Orange, The Shining \i0 and \i Fear And Loathing In Las Vegas\i0 . Yeah man, I had a blast that night." As he finished his last sentence, he glanced over at Lemmy, who nodded in agreement.\par
"And remember, Iggy" Larry continued, "When we got into Dad's cologne stash and poured it over ourselves, and smelled like the perfume section in a department store so strongly that we were ejected from school for a week because some of our classmates were vomiting?"\par
Iggy laughed heartily. He hadn't forgotten at all, and he obviously still thought of it fondly.\par
"And Morton", Larry went on, almost losing his composure completely, "Man, you gotta give it up for the way we used to play so much Tekken and Street Fighter together that we ended up burning up the disks we used them so much."\par
Morton grinned and nodded. It was the first he had smiled since he had been back at the castle.\par
"And of course I can't forget you, Ludwig.", he continued. "Remember in third grade, when that little girl fell in love with you and chased you screaming through the hallways for three days straight before she was given a stern talking to by Principal Jones?"\par
Ludwig chuckled uncontrollably. He remembered how funny it wasn't when it had happened, but it sure was now.\par
"Well", Larry choked, "I miss those days, and I know I'm not the only one that thinks so. And nothing would make me happier than to see us back together again. I'm not saying give up your hobbies, Lemmy and Iggy, or for Wendy to quit her job, or for Morton to give up living by himself if he wants to do so, but it's not right for us to stay apart like this. We've never been good on our own."\par
"We've never been good together, either", Roy quipped. "Half of the best memories we have are when we got into humoungous trouble, or did something that \b should've\b0  got us in humongous trouble, anyway."\par
"But," Larry replied, "It was almost always more than one of us that was responsible, and we had a damn good time doing it. I mean, when Wendy raided the arsenal and took more explosives than a fireworks factory makes in a year, I was the one that distracted the guards for her while she sneaked in over and over to steal the shit, was I not?" He looked over at Wendy, who was bawling but nodded enthusiastically.\par
"Now, I'm not telling any of you what to do", Larry continued, "But I know none of us want to throw all of that away just because we've grown up. Because now that we ARE adults, who's to say that we can't have more fun that we ever did before? It wouldn't take sacrificing anything on any of our parts for us to just spend some time together, even a little bit, every once in a while. And if you don't want that, that's fine. But before you decide whether you agree or disagree, consider this." He paused and took a deep breath before continuing. "I'm already feeling the pangs from the addictions I have to heroin, crack and God knows what else. And unless at least a few of you are there for me, I don't know how long I'm going to be able to last. And I don't want it to destroy me. Two, three, five, ten years down the road, I want to be there for all of you. I've never wanted anything more in my life. So, I'm going to stop talking now, because I want to hear what you have to say, and because I'm too close to losing my god damned composure to continue."\par
Both he and Wendy were emotionally wrecked, and Morton was beginning to choke up too. Though Larry didn't think nor care about it at that moment, Morton along with everyone else realized that his youngest brother's words had cut them all deeply in reminding them of how long they had neglected each other, and he wasn't about to ask about why Bowser's supposedly forgiving him hadn't been brought up at all. Though no words were spoken for what seemed like hours, almost as if on cue, all of the siblings, in turn, got up from the couches and hugged Larry and each other, some of them crying for the first time in years. No unwritten laws of society or manhood were important or thought of right now... Their only concern was to be there for Larry, and for each other, now that both his words and bleak situation had opened their eyes to what they had long forgotten was truly important... Their family.\par
After all had been embraced and reminded of how they were all appreciated, Larry wiped his eyes, and despite himself, laughed a little through the lingering mist. "The Koopa clan is back together again!", he almost shouted, filled with joy that overpowered the withdrawal that was wracking his body. Even if Roy and Morton, in their newfound reunion with him and the others, didn't decide to join him and throw away their own addictions, it would not bring him down. He could only feel joy that their eyes, like everyone else's, had been opened.\par
After that, Larry and Wendy squeezed into the little amount of room that was left on the couches, and for the first time in years, the Koopa clan talked... About what had happened to them all, about what they'd felt over the long span of time, how they were growing up, their loves and hates, desires and disgusts, just anything they could think of. In fact, by the time they realized how late it was, five hours had passed.\par
It was Morton who begrudgingly first mentioned that he couldn't stay forever. He had to get back to his apartment and get some sleep for tomorrow's work. But before he left, he made a promise to be back tomorrow, and spend however much time he could just being with his brethren, having fun and doing whatever catching up had not already been accomplished that night. And they all knew it was a promise that he would keep. So, one by one, they agreed to the same thing, and though Morton and Ludwig were obligated to leave, Iggy, Lemmy, Roy, Wendy and Larry stayed together most of the night, spending it talking, watching old movies they all used to like, and just enjoying the sense of family that had long been absent with all of them.\par
But eventually, the lights had to be turned out, and so one by one, they said their goodnights and headed into their respective rooms.\par
Larry was the last to leave, and it was somewhere around five in the morning when he closed his bedroom door, turned down the covers on the bed and readied himself to try to sleep.\par
His face was pale, there were heavy bags under his eyes and his whole body began to shake as he pulled the still-cold blanket over his neck. He knew it to be the heroin that was doing it to him, the last lingering pieces of the horrible drug determined to bring him down for neglecting to supply it with more, and his nerves somehow seemed to scream, undoubtedly at him for what he was putting them and their dependency through. If he could even sleep the rest of the night, it would be a miracle.\par
There was no denying that the next few weeks would be the hardest of his life; but somehow, in the grand scheme of things, it felt unimportant to him. He now had the people to support him and help him see every day through to the end of his temporary suffering, and the pain was a small price to pay for what it had helped to bring together again.\par
And as he gradually grew drowsy and stopped caring about the shaking and the pain, his last conscious thoughts before he entered the world of dreams were his thankfulness that he had a family once again.\par
